text: Sure, absolutely. Coming out of college, my first job opportunity was on the agency trading desk of a, actually it was a Canadian bank that had just gotten its section 20 power. So they're trading US fixed income. So I got an opportunity to trade a US agency debt on their desk as a trader. And at that point, I don't know if you recall, I'm a little older than you, Corey, but the FICO market was going on. FISLIC just went under the savings and loans crisis. That was the insurance arm of the savings and loan, and there was no funding for them. So essentially the US government had to create these bonds as a stopgap measure. They were called FICO bonds, but the banks didn't want to fund it up and the government didn't want to fund it up. So there was this battle going on. So this spread on these was through the roof, although it was backed by what I thought was the US government. It was issued by them. So why wouldn't they have the full faith and credit of the US government? So I just thought the spreads were ridiculous. And part of it was probably nice. Now that I look back, but I said, these things got to come in. So I was taking as many FICOs as I could get on the desk. I was stripping them to create zeros out of them and then selling them to my sales traders to sell to their clients. We're just pushing those. And we had a really, really good run of it. I think it made a lot of sense. They were trading three, 400 bips above the comparable treasury out. I think they went out to 2019 was the last maturity. And then I would take the principal and I'd have the hedge trade on the back end of it. And that's pretty much all I did. For two years, it was just that. Worked out really well. The government finally came in and said, yeah, we'll fund it up. Then the spread compressed. We made money on the back end as well as those. And right when that was winding up, I got a call from a headhunter who was looking to place someone at a hedge fund. And I've heard a little bit about hedge funds, but not a lot. It's not something that they really taught us in school back in the late 80s, early 90s. So I entertained it and eventually took a position at a commodity trading advisor where I... Was responsible for creating a macro trading strategy. The reason I took it is I had a lot of leeway in how I wanted to create it. There was things changing in the hedge fund industry, especially the CT industry at that time. In the late 70s, 80s, maybe even early 90s, it was the wild west. I mean, you'd have like John Henry. He had his hedge fund that could make 50% return in one year, but it could lose 60% the following year. And when I came in, investors were really... They think that they can handle that kind of volatility. They think that they can handle that kind of volatility. Until that volatility hits them. So when I created my strategies, which I know we'll get into more detail later, it was really to kind of minimize that equity curve. I didn't want to incur those bigger drawdowns in what could I do to create a strategy that people could stomach a little better than the kind of the wild west days that everyone was trying to stay away from. So I was in that space at a couple of firms for about 15, 18 years. And as I was built out some pretty good programs, developed... I had the experience in them. And at that point, at the last firm, it's called net risk, right? Where you have a firm that's set up across different functions. You may have an equity group, a CTA group, and et cetera. And a hedge fund gets paid on a watermark. So there's something called net risk. So even if you're performing very well, if the firm doesn't make money, you don't get paid. So those issues were going on. And I was kind of a little, I guess, dismayed at the industry at that point. I said, what else am I going to do? And at that point, I started... I had a young family as well. And maybe it was looking for, I don't know what was really going on in my head, but maybe looking for something a little different in terms of quality of life. And I had an opportunity with a colleague that I went to school with who was actually got involved with a group that was trading physical oil out of Nigeria. It was Bonnie Light Oil. And they needed someone to come in who had commodity experience. And that's where my CTA background came in, to hedge a physical allocation that they're getting from Nigeria as they were shipping it to the refineries in the Caribbean, where they'd refine it. And they were getting this allocation for the government, but they wanted to hedge the price as it takes up to three months in these, they call them ULCC or big tankers to get from Nigeria to the Caribbean. And obviously prices fluctuate. So my job was to hedge that going to the Caribbean. That lasted about two or three years. The allocation was gotten from the current president of Nigeria at the time, and he did not get reelected. So that allocation was going to dry up. So again, I was forced to see what I wanted to do. I was at that point, I considered going back into the CTA, the hedge fund world, but got an interesting call from someone who was, they were looking to beef up their quantitative desk at a big pension. And it was the General Motors Asset Management, the pension that defined benefit plans for General Motors. So I went in, had a couple of interviews there, and it really sparked my interest in how I could apply my past experiences to call it the pension dilemma at the time. So I worked there for about eight years, which was really interesting. We went through a lot, obviously 2008 happened at that time. GM, who was the sponsor of the pension went in chapter 11. So there's a lot of things there coming out of that, a lot of LDI, a lot of the big de-risking, the largest de-risking of a pension in history was done during my tenure there as well. So I got to learn a lot of things about a lot of different things. And then most recently, I had an opportunity to kind of jump over to UPS, which had similar characteristics, I'd say to GM when I was there in 08, and they wanted someone to come in, kind of guide that ship as they were going from an asset only perspective to more of a asset liability management, or as they say, ALM perspective, and kind of drive that initiative at UPS. And I've been there running the strategy and allocation group at UPS for about five years now.
